# Technical Risk and Information Security Considerations

Because the proposed target is an AI-enabled operational system that will directly influence delivery promises, driver instructions, customer notifications, and routing decisions at scale, technical and information-security risks must be treated as core ERM concerns rather than as standalone IT issues.

Unlike conventional software acquisitions, a failure in this system would simultaneously generate operational disruption, financial loss, regulatory liability, and reputational damage. The following risk categories each carry cross-domain ERM consequences and must be monitored through dedicated KRIs and governance controls.

## Model Risk

The optimization algorithm may prioritize speed or cost efficiency while systematically underweighting driver safety, weather hazards, parking limitations, accessibility requirements, or legal break obligations.

If unchecked, this creates operational liability, labor regulatory violations, and personal injury exposure that would be attributed to Amazon’s acquisition decision and AI governance practices.

## Model Drift

Route performance may degrade over time as customer demand patterns, traffic conditions, local regulations, or delivery station operations evolve beyond the model’s training data.

Without a continuous model validation process and drift detection alerts, performance degradation may go undetected until it manifests as widespread delivery failures—creating a process risk that is both operationally costly and reputationally damaging.

## Cyber Risk

The acquired system’s APIs, routing data stores, real-time driver geolocation feeds, customer home addresses, and delivery proof photographs constitute a high-value attack surface.

A ransomware attack, API breach, or unauthorized access event would not only disrupt delivery operations at scale, but would trigger CCPA enforcement liability, multi-state consumer notification obligations, and reputational harm in a domain where Amazon has not previously faced this level of logistics data security scrutiny.

## Data Privacy Risk

The acquisition would significantly expand the volume and sensitivity of personal and operational data under Amazon’s control, including customer delivery addresses linked to behavioral patterns, driver location histories, and biometric or photographic delivery confirmations.

This data must be governed under CCPA, applicable state privacy laws, and Amazon’s own data retention standards—creating compliance obligations that require a dedicated privacy impact assessment and ongoing data lifecycle management before and after integration.

## Resilience Risk

If the acquired service becomes unavailable during peak delivery periods such as Prime Day or the holiday season, the absence of tested fallback routing and manual dispatch procedures would cause cascading delivery failures across hundreds of stations simultaneously.

System resilience is therefore an ERM concern, not merely an IT continuity issue, because downtime directly translates into SLA failures, customer compensation costs, and brand damage at the moments of highest public and operational visibility.
